The Beck family, three generations strong, set out to harvest disease-free oysters after years of waiting.
Oystermen agreed to wait until the oysters reached legal size, leading to a decline in the industry.
Efforts to introduce Asian oysters face scrutiny for safety concerns.
Cleanup initiatives struggle to meet deadlines amidst bureaucratic hurdles.
The Chesapeake Bay's decline is attributed to pollution and sewage runoff.
Despite challenges, oyster-packing companies like Harris continue to preserve the bay's heritage.
Festivals and contests celebrate the bay's rich oyster culture, a tradition worth preserving for future generations.
